Multimodal Modeling and Deployment Phase: Comparative Analysis With and Without PCA under the MLflow Lifecycle for New Sample Inference

This repository corresponds to Phase 3: Modeling and Predictions, in which different machine learning approaches are developed and evaluated using the dataset previously loaded and preprocessed in the earlier phases. This stage addresses models based on K-Nearest Neighbors, Neural Networks, dimensionality reduction techniques using PCA, and clustering methods, including comparisons between scenarios with and without PCA, with the aim of analyzing their impact on model performance. The index for this phase is presented below.

warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
mlflow.set_tracking_uri("file:../mlruns")

SEED = 42
np.random.seed(SEED)
tf.random.set_seed(SEED)

def compute_metrics(y_true, y_pred):
    return {
        "accuracy": accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred),
        "precision": precision_score(y_true, y_pred),
        "recall": recall_score(y_true, y_pred),
        "f1_score": f1_score(y_true, y_pred)
    }

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, name):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", ax=ax)
    ax.set_xlabel("Predicted")
    ax.set_ylabel("True")
    fig.tight_layout()
    
    save_path = f"{name}_cm.png"
    fig.savefig(save_path)
    mlflow.log_artifact(save_path)
    os.remove(save_path)
    plt.close(fig)
    #return fig

The two- and three-dimensional PCA projections were used exclusively for exploratory and interpretative purposes. By visualizing the data in reduced spaces defined by the first two and three principal components, it is possible to qualitatively assess the degree of class separation and the underlying geometric structure of the dataset. Although these low-dimensional projections capture only a limited portion of the total variance, they provide valuable insight into how the samples are distributed and whether any coarse patterns or groupings emerge in relation to the target variable.

In both the 2D and 3D visualizations, partial overlap between classes is observed, which is consistent with the multifactorial nature of the problem. This overlap indicates that no small subset of components is sufficient to fully separate the classes, reinforcing the idea that the predictive signal is distributed across multiple dimensions. As a result, these visualizations serve as diagnostic tools rather than as a basis for aggressive dimensionality reduction.

2.3 PCA full variables

The full PCA transformation, computed using all available components, was employed to quantitatively analyze the variance distribution and to guide the selection of an appropriate number of components for modeling. The analysis shows that the explained variance accumulates gradually, requiring 11 components to exceed the 80% variance threshold. This behavior reflects low redundancy among features and suggests that the original feature space contains complementary information across dimensions.

2.4 Select PCA to Geometric dataset

Based on the PCA results, the dimensionality of the geometric dataset was reduced by retaining the first 17 principal components, as they collectively explain approximately 82.5% of the total variance. This selection exceeds the predefined 80% variance threshold, ensuring that most of the original information is preserved while reducing the dimensionality of the feature space. The remaining components contribute marginally to the explained variance and were therefore excluded to avoid unnecessary complexity without significant informational gain.

def run_knn_experiment(
    X_train, X_test,
    y_train, y_test,
    k, metric,
    use_pca=False,
    confidence_threshold=0.95,
    artifact_prefix="knn",
    n_components= 17
    
    ):
    run_name = f"KNN_k{k}_{metric}_PCA_{use_pca}"

    with mlflow.start_run(run_name=run_name):
        mlflow.log_params({
            "n_neighbors": k,
            "distance_metric": metric,
            "use_pca": use_pca,
            "confidence_threshold": confidence_threshold,
            "n_components": n_components
        })

        knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k, metric=metric)
        knn.fit(X_train, y_train)

        y_proba = knn.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
        y_pred = (y_proba >= confidence_threshold).astype(int)

        metrics = compute_metrics(y_test, y_pred)
        mlflow.log_metrics(metrics)


        mlflow.sklearn.log_model(
            sk_model=knn, 
            artifact_path="model", 
            registered_model_name=None
        )
        
        plot_confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred, f"{artifact_prefix}_k{k}_{metric}")

def build_ann_model(input_dim, config):
    model = tf.keras.Sequential()
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(input_dim,)))
    for layer in config["layers"]:
        model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(layer["units"], activation=layer["activation"]))
        if layer["dropout"] > 0:
            model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(layer["dropout"]))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    model.compile(
        optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=config["learning_rate"]),
        loss="binary_crossentropy"
    )
    return model

def run_ann_experiment(
    X_train,
    X_test,
    y_train,
    y_test,
    config,
    use_pca=False, 
    epochs=50,
    batch_size=32,
    confidence_threshold=0.95,
    artifact_prefix="ann",
    n_components = 17
    ):
    run_name = f"{config['name']}_PCA_{use_pca}"
    with mlflow.start_run(run_name=run_name):
        mlflow.log_params({
            "model": "ANN",
            "use_pca": use_pca,
            "architecture": str(config["layers"]),
            "learning_rate": config["learning_rate"],
            "epochs": epochs,
            "batch_size": batch_size,
            "prediction_threshold": confidence_threshold,
            "n_components": n_components

        })

        model = build_ann_model(X_train.shape[1], config)
        model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=epochs, batch_size=batch_size, verbose=0)

        y_proba = model.predict(X_test, verbose=0).ravel()
        y_pred = (y_proba >= confidence_threshold).astype(int)

        mlflow.log_metrics(compute_metrics(y_test, y_pred))

        mlflow.tensorflow.log_model(model=model, artifact_path="model")

        plot_name = f"{artifact_prefix}_{config['name']}_PCA_{use_pca}"
        plot_confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred, plot_name)

def graficar_grafo_bayeseano(modelo_grafo, target_name, filename):
    G = nx.DiGraph()
    G.add_edges_from(modelo_grafo.edges())
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(25, 15))
    pos = nx.spring_layout(G, k=5.0, iterations=200, seed=42)
    
    nodos_target = [n for n in G.nodes() if n == target_name]
    nodos_otros = [n for n in G.nodes() if n != target_name]
    
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos, nodelist=nodos_otros, node_color='#A0CBE2', 
                           node_size=4500, alpha=0.8, edgecolors='#333333', linewidths=1.2)
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos, nodelist=nodos_target, node_color='#FF8C00', 
                           node_size=6500, alpha=1.0, edgecolors='#CC5500', linewidths=3)
    
    nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos, font_size=10, font_weight='bold', font_family='sans-serif')
    
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos, edgelist=G.edges(), edge_color='#444444', 
                           width=2.2, arrows=True, arrowsize=35, 
                           connectionstyle='arc3,rad=0.2', 
                           min_source_margin=25, min_target_margin=25)
    
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.savefig(filename, format="png", dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
    plt.show()

experiment_names = ['KNN_Models', 'BN_Models', 'ANN_Models', 'Cluster_Models']

best_models = {}

for name in experiment_names:
    exp = mlflow.get_experiment_by_name(name)
    if exp is None: continue
    
    runs_df = mlflow.search_runs(
        experiment_ids=[exp.experiment_id],
        max_results=1,
        order_by=["metrics.accuracy DESC"]
    )
    
    if not runs_df.empty:
        best_run = runs_df.iloc[0]
        run_id = best_run['run_id']
        
        results_list.append({
            "Experiment": name,
            "Accuracy": best_run.get("metrics.accuracy", 0),
            "Precision": best_run.get("metrics.precision", 0),
            "Recall": best_run.get("metrics.recall", 0),
            "F1": best_run.get("metrics.f1_score", 0)
        })

        path = "model_bayesian" if name == 'BN_Models' else "model"
        model_uri = f"runs:/{run_id}/{path}"
        
        cluster_map = None
        if name == 'Cluster_Models':
            local_path = mlflow.artifacts.download_artifacts(run_id=run_id, artifact_path="cluster_dict.json")
            with open(local_path, "r") as f:
                raw_map = json.load(f)
            cluster_map = {int(k): v for k, v in raw_map.items()}

        best_models[name] = {
            "model_obj": mlflow.pyfunc.load_model(model_uri),
            "use_pca": str(best_run.get("params.use_pca", "False")) == "True",
            "n_components": int(float(best_run.get("params.n_components", 0))),
            "cluster_map": cluster_map,
            "run_id": run_id
        }

for i, sample in enumerate(test_cases):
    tag = f"Case_{i+1}"
    input_row = pd.DataFrame([sample], columns=cols)
    
    input_for_trans = input_row.drop(columns=['ASD_TARGET']) if 'ASD_TARGET' in input_row.columns else input_row
    
    data_trans = loaded_trasnformer_geometric.transform(input_for_trans)
    data_scaled = loaded_scaler.transform(data_trans)

    if 'KNN_Models' in best_models:
        model_info = best_models['KNN_Models']
        knn_raw = model_info['model_obj']._model_impl.sklearn_model
        knn_input = loaded_pca_full.transform(data_scaled)[:, :17] 
        prob = knn_raw.predict_proba(knn_input)[0, 1]
        res = "Yes" if prob >= 0.8 else "No"
        results_summary.append([tag, "KNN", f"{prob*100:.2f}%", res])

    if 'ANN_Models' in best_models:
        model_info = best_models['ANN_Models']
        res_ann = model_info['model_obj'].predict(data_scaled)
        prob_ann = float(np.ravel(res_ann)[0])
        res = "Yes" if prob_ann >= 0.8 else "No"
        results_summary.append([tag, "ANN", f"{prob_ann*100:.2f}%", res])

    if 'Cluster_Models' in best_models:
        model_info = best_models['Cluster_Models']
        cluster_raw = model_info['model_obj']._model_impl.sklearn_model
        
        if model_info['use_pca']:
            n = model_info['n_components']
            pca_model = loaded_pca_2 if n == 2 else (loaded_pca_3 if n == 3 else loaded_pca_full)
            cluster_input = pca_model.transform(data_scaled)
            if n == 17: cluster_input = cluster_input[:, :17]
        else:
            cluster_input = data_scaled
            
        cluster_id = int(cluster_raw.predict(cluster_input)[0])
        mode_vote = model_info['cluster_map'].get(cluster_id, 0)
        res = "Yes" if mode_vote == 1 else "No"
        results_summary.append([tag, "Cluster", f"ID:{cluster_id}", res])

if 'BN_Models' in best_models:
    test_df = pd.DataFrame(test_cases, columns=cols).drop(columns=['ASD_TARGET'])
    bn_raw = loaded_trasnformer_bayesian.transform(test_df)
    bn_df = pd.DataFrame(bn_raw, columns=loaded_trasnformer_bayesian.get_feature_names_out())
    
    mapping = {c: n for c in bn_df.columns for n in nodos_modelo if n.lower() in c.lower()}
    bn_input = bn_df.rename(columns=mapping).loc[:, ~bn_df.rename(columns=mapping).columns.duplicated()]
    
    for n in nodos_modelo: 
        if n not in bn_input.columns: bn_input[n] = 0
        
    bn_input = bn_input[nodos_modelo].apply(lambda x: np.clip(x, 0, 3)).astype(np.int64)
    probs_bn = np.ravel(best_models['BN_Models']['model_obj'].predict(bn_input))

    for idx, prob in enumerate(probs_bn):
        results_summary.append([f"Case_{idx+1}", "Bayesian", f"{float(prob)*100:.2f}%", "Yes" if float(prob) >= 0.8 else "No"])

9. Conclusion

  • Consensus in Case 1 shows total alignment in the first test scenario where 100.00% of the models identified the positive risk profile. This agreement between KNN, ANN, and the Bayesian model validates the label consistency in cases with a high density of symptoms. The Neural Network specifically reached a 99.91% certainty probability reaffirming the precision of connectionist architectures on this dataset.

  • Global performance metrics indicate that the Artificial Neural Network model achieved a final Accuracy of 0.9290 and an F1-score of 0.8484. For its part the K-Nearest Neighbors algorithm reported an Accuracy of 0.8794 maintaining a perfect Precision of 1.0000 for positive classes. These indicators demonstrate that the transformations applied during the feature engineering phase were effective for supervised learning.

  • Bayesian Network effectiveness stands out as the only system with a 100.00% sensitivity when detecting positive risk across all test cases. While the KNN and ANN models yielded a 0.00% probability in the second scenario the Bayesian model maintained its absolute detection. This superior predictive capacity in borderline cases highlights the importance of using probabilistic graphs to capture conditional dependencies.

  • Optimization and Clustering through the reduction to 17 principal components allowed capturing the necessary variance to reach a 0.9432 precision. The unsupervised analysis successfully linked the subject of the first case with Cluster ID 14 which concentrates the main risk indicators. This approach allowed eliminating noise from irrelevant variables optimizing the grouping of adult profiles with suspected autism traits.

  • Numerical stability and hardware were guaranteed through oneDNN and XLA optimizations ensuring the 0.22% result for the ANN was consistent. This infrastructure allowed processing the 29 original features and the 17 transformed ones with total stability during the inference phase. The use of hardware acceleration ensures the system's scalability for future massive model analysis phases within the broader project.

  • Divergence in critical scenarios revealed that in the second case the structural KNN and ANN models reported a 0.00% risk probability. This discrepancy against the 100.00% obtained by the Bayesian Network suggests that spatial models require much higher activation thresholds. The analysis proves that probabilistic logic detects early warnings where traditional classifiers fail due to the data distribution.

  • Data engineering strategy through the separation of pipelines allowed the Bayesian Network to achieve an Accuracy of 1.0000 during validation. Preserving original categorical variables allowed the Bayesian graph to operate on direct relationships without numerical scaling distortion. This methodology ensures that each architecture works with the optimal data format according to its own mathematical and logical nature.

  • Third scenario analysis presented a significant challenge where the KNN model showed a 25.00% probability and the ANN only 0.22%. Again the Bayesian model maintained a 100.00% confidence confirming its robustness against profiles with less evident autism symptoms. Linking this case with Cluster ID 12 reinforces the existence of subgroups with subtle characteristics that require a causal analysis.

  • Integrated prediction capability allowed validating adult profiles through a high-fidelity multi-architectural approach based on real-world data results. The metrics obtained through MLflow document the consistency of hyperparameters and the success of the training phase on the dataset. The complete workflow from EDA to inference ensures the system can handle new cases with verifiable and statistically significant metrics.
